<p>This folio contains two primary types of paper: sheets with a small fleur-de-lis
and an "IV" countermark, and sheets with a larger fleur-de-lis and no apparent 
countermark.  In the former instance, I photographed both mark and countermark.  The
folio's size and flexible binding made for relatively easy photographing, although
the heavy amount of text over some of the marks makes it a challenge
to interpret them.  Yet, by digitally enhancing the marks and superimposing
them upon one another, we can get a good sense of their relationship to one another.
For example, a simple animation program helps to reveal that the watermarks on leaves

<a href="javascript:newWin('http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/watermarks/1717/overlaya.gif', 'overlay')">
g1 and Sss2</a>
quite possibly came from the same mold, while the marks on 
<a href="javascript:newWin('http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/watermarks/1717/overlayb.gif', 'overlayb')">
g1 and c1</a> are
certainly different.

